That's a great start! Using `std::arch::is_x86_feature_detected!` is idiomatic for checking CPU features at runtime in Rust. However, you should be cautious about safety implications if the feature isn't detected. If your code calls AVX2 instructions even when undetected, it'll crash or exhibit undefined behavior. So, wrapping unsafe code inside a feature check is crucial: `if cfg!(feature="avx2") { unsafe { ... } }`. For dispatching implementations based on CPU features, you can use something like this:

```rust
fn get_impl() -> Box<dyn MyTrait> {
    if std::arch::is_x86_feature_detected!("avx2") {
        Box::new(Avx2Impl {})
    } else {
        Box::new(DefaultImpl {})
    }
}
``` But remember, even better is to detect CPU features at runtime using `cpuid` syscalls (via the `cpuid` crate) or assembly instructions. This gives more accuracy and avoids compiler optimizations that might strip out feature checks.
